        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We seek to resolve the broad-line absorption filaments in HCO+ (1-0) which 
are unresolved in our Cycle 0 observations (1.7'' beam). 

Correlator setup:

We allocate spectral windows for our main line, HCO+ (1-0) as well as for 
a comparable molecule which shows no broad-line absorption filaments in our 
coarser Cycle 0 observations (HCN (1-0)). We also include optically thin 
isotopologues of these lines. In the upper side band, we place transitions 
of H2CS (which is a good tracer of other continuum features in the rest 
of the Brick) and CS 2-1, which traces lower density gas. We cannot 
place N2H+ (1-0) and HCO+ (1-0) in the same correlator setup, so 
N2H+ (1-0) is observed in our other science goal. Our Cycle 0 observations 
had coarse velocity resolution (3 km/s). We increase our velocity resolution 
to 0.2 km/s in order to see if the filaments exhibit fine velocity structure, 
although we may have to bin in velocity to achieve sufficient signal to noise. 
This setup maintains broad enough velocity coverage to sample the whole cloud 
(from 0 to 100 km/s).

Imaging:

Only a single pointing is necessary to cover large portions of the two 
strongest filaments. We do not need to map the whole filament; establishing 
the width in a single ALMA FOV is sufficient to constrain its physical nature. 

Sensitivity:

It is most important that we detect HCO+ (1-0) absorption with our original 
velocity resolution. Therefore, we calculate the sensitivity over a 3 km/s 
bandwidth. Since we are seeing absorption against emission with a 3 K 
brightness temperature emission, we need to be sensitive to roughly 0.6 K in 
order to get a 5 sigma detection. Note that we can tolerate the low signal to 
noise ratio since we already know exactly where the narrow features should 
be present.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
