        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since we cannot include N2H+ (1-0) at the same time as HCO+ (1-0), we observe it
separately at lower angular resolution. This lower angular resolution is the 
conservative choice. If the absorption filament is actually as extended as 1.7 
arcseconds and the N2H+ (1-0) transition is somewhat weaker than the HCO+ (1-0) 
transition, we will still have sufficient sensitivity to detect the absorption 
filament. We do not need higher angular resolution for this science goal since 
the mere presence of these absoprtion filaments in both ionic species would be 
definitive evidence that the filaments are ordered by magnetic fields. 

Correlator setup:

We target N2H+ (1-0) as our main priority, and include the optically thin 
N15NH+ (1-0) as well. In the upper side band we include transitions for H2CS, 
which proved to be a good tracer of continuum emission in our Cycle 0 
observations of the Brick. Our main goal is to detect N2H+ (1-0). We search 
for velocity subtructure in the filament with high velocity resolution 
(0.2 km/s), which still allows us to cover the full range of velocities 
present in the source. We can smooth in velocity to boost our signal to noise 
if required.

Imaging:

If the absorption filament is due to ionic gyration around magnetic field 
lines, then it will be of comparable size for N2H+ (1-0) and HCO+ (1-0). For 
this reason, we assume that the narrow dimesion will be as extended as 1.7 
arcseconds. A single pointing will cover enough of the filaments to make the 
comparison between N2H+ (1-0) and HCO+ (1-0).

Sensitivity:

If the explanation for the absorbing filament is ionic gyration around magnetic 
field lines, then we expect that the absorption strength in N2H+ (1-0) will be 
comparable to the absorption strength in HCO+ (1-0). From single dish data 
we expect the that bright background in N2H+ (1-0) will be at least 2K. We 
target a sensitivity of 0.1 K in a 3 km/s bandwidth, which would give a 
solid 20 sigma detection. This signal-to-noise ratio at this velocity 
resolution will allow us to make a comparable analsysis of the depth of the 
absorption filament with our HCO+ (1-0) data from Cycle 0. We will have 
sufficient sensitivity to look for somewhat finer velocity structure in the 
absorption profile.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
